SIMPLE: sullen
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sullen
<hw>Sul"len</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>solein</ets>, <ets>solain</ets>, lonely, sullen; through Old French
fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>solanus</ets> solitary, fr. L. <ets>solus</ets>
alone. See <er>Sole</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Lonely;
solitary; desolate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wyclif (Job iii.
14).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Gloomy; dismal; foreboding.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Solemn hymns so <qex>sullen</qex> dirges change.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mischievous; malignant; unpropitious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such <qex>sullen</qex> planets at my birth did shine.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Gloomily angry and silent; cross; sour; affected
with ill humor; morose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>sullen</qex> I forsook the imperfect feast.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Obstinate; intractable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Things are as <qex>sullen</qex> as we are.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Heavy; dull; sluggish.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The larger
stream was placid, and even <xex>sullen</xex>, in its course.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sulky; sour; cross; ill-natured; morose; peevish;
fretful; ill-humored; petulant; gloomy; malign; intractable.</syn> --
<usage><er>Sullen</er>, <er>Sulky</er>. Both <xex>sullen</xex> and
<xex>sulky</xex> show themselves in the demeanor. <xex>Sullenness</xex>
seems to be an habitual sulkiness, and <xex>sulkiness</xex> a temporary
sullenness. The former may be an innate disposition; the latter, a
disposition occasioned by recent injury. Thus we are in a
<xex>sullen</xex> mood, and in a <xex>sulky</xex> fit.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No cheerful breeze this <qex>sullen</qex> region knows;⟦br⟧
The dreaded east is all the wind that blows.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Sul"len*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Sul"len*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sullen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sullen
<hw>Sul"len</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who is solitary, or
lives alone; a hermit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Piers
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Sullen feelings or manners; sulks;
moroseness; <as>as, to have the <ex>sullens</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sullen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sullen
<hw>Sul"len</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make sullen or
sluggish.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sullens</qex> the whole body with . . . laziness.</q>
<rj><qau>Feltham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sullevate</ent>⟦br⟧
